---
name: youtube-to-steps
description: >
  Activate when the user provides a YouTube URL and wants it converted into
  actionable steps. Triggers on: "/youtube-to-steps <url>", "/youtube-to-steps <url> <N>",
  "turn this video into steps", "summarize youtube video as steps",
  "extract steps from this video", or any YouTube URL accompanied by "steps"
  or "how to follow". N is optional — skill auto-determines step count if omitted.
---

# youtube-to-steps — Orchestration Instructions

Claude orchestrates three agents: Gemini (video extraction) → Claude (formatting
& validation) → Codex (code review). Output is always saved to a markdown file.

---

## Step 1 — Parse input

Extract from the user's message:
- `YOUTUBE_URL`: the full YouTube URL (must start with `https://www.youtube.com/` or `https://youtu.be/`)
- `N`: the number of steps requested (integer). **Optional** — if not provided, Gemini will auto-determine the appropriate count based on video length and complexity. Do NOT ask the user for N.

Derive a short `VIDEO_SLUG` from the URL for the output filename:
- For `?v=<id>` URLs: use the video ID
- For `youtu.be/<id>` URLs: use the ID

Output file path: `~/documents/youtube-steps/<VIDEO_SLUG>-steps.md`

---

## Step 2 — Run Gemini extraction

Run the extraction script from the skill directory:

```bash
# With auto N (recommended when user didn't specify):
cd ~/.claude/skills/youtube-to-steps && python3 extract_steps.py "<YOUTUBE_URL>"

# With explicit N:
cd ~/.claude/skills/youtube-to-steps && python3 extract_steps.py "<YOUTUBE_URL>" <N>
```

- If the script exits with a non-zero code, show the stderr output and stop.
- Parse the JSON array from stdout. Each item has: `step`, `title`, `detail`.

---

## Step 3 — Validate and format steps (Claude)

Review the steps:
1. Confirm exactly N steps exist. If not, merge or split steps to reach N.
2. Ensure each step title starts with an action verb.
3. Ensure each detail is self-contained (no references like "as above" or "see step 2").
4. Preserve all code blocks verbatim.

Format as markdown:

```markdown
# Steps: <video title or URL>
**Source:** <YOUTUBE_URL>
**Steps:** <N>

---

## Step 1: <title>
<detail>

## Step 2: <title>
<detail>

...
```

Hold this markdown in context — do NOT show it yet.

---

## Step 4 — Always run Codex code review

Always run Codex regardless of whether steps contain code:

```bash
codex exec "Review these instructional steps for accuracy, completeness, and any code correctness issues. Flag anything misleading or technically incorrect. Be concise.\n\n<paste full markdown steps here>"
```

Parse Codex output. Append to the markdown as:

```markdown
---

## Code Review (Codex)
<codex output verbatim>
```

If Codex errors or times out, note it: `> Codex review unavailable: <error>`

---

## Step 5 — Save to file

Write the complete markdown (steps + code review section) to:
`~/documents/youtube-steps/<VIDEO_SLUG>-steps.md`

Then tell the user:
- File path
- Number of steps extracted
- Any warnings (step count mismatch, Codex error)

Do NOT print the full step content to the terminal — just the summary.
